xnumpy allows writing user-scheduled SIMD kernels in pure Python.
It lowers Exo scheduling-language kernels through xDSL (Python-
native MLIR) and JIT-compiles them to native vector code via
llvmlite's MCJIT entirely in-process, without a C compilation step.

The programmer writes a kernel, applies scheduling transforms
(e.g. tiling, vectorization, unrolling), and obtains a callable
native function pointer.

How it works:

      Exo Python source
          v
      Exo LoopIR
          v
    - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - -  xDSL
      MLIR module
          v
      MLIR LLVM dialect
          v
    - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - - llvmlite
      Native code

Write your own kernels:

    $ uv run xnumpy examples/demo.py --mlir
    $ uv run xnumpy examples/demo.py --asm
    $ uv run xnumpy examples/demo.py --c
    $ uv run python examples/demo.py # jit

References:

- https://github.com/xdslproject/xdsl/blob/main/README.md
- https://github.com/exo-lang/exo/blob/main/docs/README.md
- https://github.com/kaylendog/exo-mlir
